 {"id":"br-r37-c1-95ayv","title":"parity: voronoi_cells raises NetworkXError instead of ValueError on empty centers","description":"fnx.voronoi_cells(G, set()) raises NetworkXError('center_nodes must not be empty'); nx raises ValueError('sources must not be empty'). Drop-in code catching ValueError to handle empty-centers gracefully fails on fnx (NetworkXError isn't a ValueError subclass). Fix: change to ValueError and align message with nx exactly.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T07:27:52.934359641Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T07:29:25.972596304Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T07:29:25.970740841Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit 4c24336. voronoi_cells now raises ValueError with nx's message on empty centers. 6 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-9fa26","title":"parity: core_number dict iterates in sorted-key order, nx iterates in node-insertion order","description":"fnx.core_number returns a dict with keys sorted (e.g. [0,1,2,3,4]) regardless of node-insertion order. nx returns the dict in node-insertion order (e.g. [2,3,0,1,4] when edges were added in (2,3),(0,1),... order). Same iteration-order family as br-r37-c1-pm78h (communicability_betweenness_centrality) and br-r37-c1-f6epo (second_order_centrality). Drop-in code that relies on the iteration order matches nx breaks. Fix: reorder result dict in iteration order of G.nodes().","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T10:22:48.157628797Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T10:24:58.180811023Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T10:24:58.178860072Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit 58e7d6d. core_number now iterates in node-insertion order matching nx. 6 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-9kyjl","title":"parity: articulation_points + biconnected_component_edges yield in non-DFS order vs nx","description":"fnx.articulation_points returns ['b', 'c', 'd'] (alphabetical/sorted); nx returns ['d', 'b', 'c'] (DFS-discovery order). fnx.biconnected_component_edges yields edge tuples in canonical (lower-id-first) form; nx yields them in DFS-traversal direction (e.g. ('b', 'a') instead of ('a', 'b'). Drop-in code that iterates these in algorithm-discovery order breaks. Fix: delegate to nx for both functions.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T12:51:50.591176328Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T12:54:39.128658453Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T12:54:39.126665138Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit d8ef305. articulation_points and biconnected_component_edges now delegate to nx for DFS-discovery order. 7 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
-{"id":"br-r37-c1-9l73c","title":"johnson all-pairs shortest path inner-dict iteration order drifts from nx","description":"fnx.johnson returned inner-dict keys in Bellman-Ford-tree-discovery order, but nx returns them in johnson's per-node Dijkstra iteration order.

Repro:
  edges = [('a','b',1),('b','c',2),('c','d',1),('a','d',5),('b','d',3)]
  fnx.johnson(g)['a'].keys() -> ['a','b','d','c']
  nx.johnson(g)['a'].keys()  -> ['a','b','c','d']
  fnx.johnson(g)['c'].keys() -> ['c','b','d','a']
  nx.johnson(g)['c'].keys()  -> ['c','d','b','a']

Drop-in code that iterated the inner dicts of johnson() in order (e.g. for plotting paths or computing per-target metrics) silently broke.

Fix: delegate johnson to nx via _call_networkx_for_parity (same pattern as the all_pairs_dijkstra inner-dict order fixes from prior beads).","status":"in_progress","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T15:26:54.814041773Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T15:28:00.644435654Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
